<br>
-Buy a brand spanking new 2004.  Use your 2k as a downpayment.  Drive it off the lot and have it immediately depreciate 30%.  Have it depreciate another 20% by the same time next year.<br>
<br>
-Buy a couple year old used car.  Use your 2k as a downpayment.  For exchange for a few nicks and dents, stains and miles, you get a car thats well past the steep portion of the depreciation curve.  You can use the almost gone original warrenty, or you can spend a few bucks and get an extention.  Rental dealerships are great sources, you can be pretty sure that they treat the cars well, although they tend to have higher milage than your average used car.<br>
<br>
-Buy a dangerously old used car.  For 2k, you get the whole thing.  At this point most cars are starting to hit the point where major repairs/replacements are a fact of life.  You might get 1-3 more years of trouble free use from it, or you may have to throw $800 at a new transmition tomorrow.<br>
<br>
-Buy a 300$ beater.  The heater wont work, the doors wont lock, and the brakes may fail tomorrow.  When it dies its final death, walk away and buy another 300$ beater.  If you get more than 2 months use out of it, you come out ahead (assuming buying a new or slightly used car will set you on a 250-300ish dollar a month payment plan).<br>
<br>
Personally, I take option 2, but I know a few cheap/poor/I-like-to-tinker friends that go for option 4 every time. <p>Ninen of Saryrn<br>
