<br>
Oil - (Make sure the oil isn't freshly changed, this might mean the car has a serious engine problem they are covering up). If it has fresh oil, insist on driving the car 50 miles or more before buying.<br>
<br>
Brakes - make sure the condition of the brakes, this is a safety issue and you don't want them to have major problems.<br>
<br>
Air Filters - Check them, small item but important.<br>
<br>
Gas Filters - Have them checked &amp; Replaced.<br>
<br>
Coolant - Check it and replace it ASAP. There should be no contamination.<br>
<br>
Check for major rust on the body and exhaust.<br>
<br>
Have a leakdown test performed on all cylinders.<br>
<br>
There is more but these are major items. If you don't mind having a car payment and have decent credit, I recommend looking around for a good used car. To give you an Idea we bought my wife a 2002 Subaru Impreza with 13,400 miles and 2.5 years left on the warranty for 13,500 and with $1,000 down our monthly payment is $261 and the term is 60 months. This was a very good deal but gives you an idea of what is available. If you also have good credit you could look into a new car like a KIA or something similar with a great warranty. I bet you could get your payment well under 200 bucks for a 48 or 60 month loan.<br>
<br>
~Cerr<br>
